The mhd_assert macro is defined as ((void)0). Thus the statement mhd_assert(0 != param->value.len); expands to a no-op ((void)0); it is executed but has no effect, and removing it would not change program behaviour. This constitutes dead code and therefore violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.2.
</scenario>
